@flexiarg relationship-coherence/co-regulation
@title Hold the Wobble, Don't Fix It
@sigils [🫂/懐]
@keywords co-regulation, distress, felt-security, overwhelm, frazzled, anxiety, held-tension, nervous-system, therapy, comfort, mutual-repair
@audience two people weathering acute distress about the relationship itself
@references [relationship-coherence/rupture-repair relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring relationship-coherence/body-attunement]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-05-04 — Joe, 'this is to my knowledge the first time I have felt upset about anything to do with you... the validity of my relationship to you at all is being called into question left and right and it makes me feel diminished... I have been holding more tension than I was letting on,' met by Julia's 'Don't you worry about it 🫂 Maybe we can call... It's been a tricky few days, hasn't it?' (trigger: friends questioning the age-gap pairing and the 'girlfriend' label; accumulation beat 2026-05-01, Chris 'doesn't think we're a good pairing'). Recurs bidirectionally: 2026-05-19 Julia 'still feeling a bit emotionally frazzled and might appreciate a bit more alone-time today to recover... post-therapy (4pm)'; 2026-06-15 Joe's anxieties 'expressed in a worrying way' kept Julia awake -> Julia 'sad and sick at the thought of having made you feel distressed' -> repair by call, 'next time we would approach it all very differently,' and 🫂🫂🫂; muted late instance 2026-06-22 'the sensitivity... calmed way down after the conversation and reflection. I am feeling confidence in us.' Therapy recurs as a self-regulation anchor across instances."]
@tone tender
@style pattern

! conclusion: When accumulated tension about the relationship's felt security surfaces as acute distress — one of you frazzled, diminished, or spilling anxiety in a worrying way — name it plainly as distress, give space to self-regulate (therapy, alone-time) or receive the spill without taking it personally, and co-regulate with a call and physical comfort (🫂) rather than solving it; what is wounded is felt security, not logistics, and it mends nervous-system to nervous-system.

  + context: Distinct from the light rupture-repair of a single in-the-moment over-spill: here the tension has been held and accumulating, the wound is to the relationship's very standing/security (often under external pressure — friends questioning an age-gap pairing, a career knock, sleep-deprivation), and repair runs through space + co-regulation + meta-reflection rather than a quick de-personalising. Bidirectional across the corpus (Joe 2026-05-04, 2026-06-15; Julia 2026-05-19). Emerges mid-correspondence (~page 60) but was previously hidden inside capacity-honoring and rupture-repair.

  + IF:
    accumulated, previously-held tension about the relationship's felt security breaks the surface as acute distress — one party frazzled / diminished / anxiety-spilling — and the reflex is to smooth it over, argue the content, or fix the logistics.

  + HOWEVER:
    giving space is not abandonment and receiving a spill is not endorsing it; co-regulation must not tip into fixing/solving (which misreads a security wound as a problem) nor into fusing — one person's dysregulation must be allowed its own self-regulation (therapy, alone-time), not absorbed whole by the other.

  + THEN:
    name it plainly as distress and own it mutually (each may fear they diminished/distressed the other); when the need is space, grant self-regulation without personalising it (see relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring); when it spills, receive it without taking it personally; then co-regulate — a call, physical comfort (🫂), and meta-repair ("next time we would approach it differently") — and let felt security be restored before returning to the content.

  + BECAUSE:
    external devaluation and accumulated strain wound felt security, not logistics; a security wound mends nervous-system to nervous-system — through holding, space, and being plainly received — not through argument or solutions, and weathering one together deepens the very security that was shaken.

  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: acute relational distress is named, given room to self-regulate, and met with co-regulation (call / 🫂 / meta-repair). Failing when: it is smoothed over or argued as content (missing the security wound), when 'help' becomes fixing, or when one nervous system is absorbed rather than steadied. Failure twin: smoothing-over / fix-the-feeling. (Bidirectional; therapy a recurring regulation anchor. Heavier sibling of relationship-coherence/rupture-repair.)
